{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2e560daa-3501-46f8-9445-e943428763cd","content":"On macOS without `createdump`, you can use the OS-native crash reporting:\n\n1. **Check for Apple crash logs** – macOS automatically writes `.ips` / `.crash` files to:\n   - `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n   - `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\n2. **Enable core dumps** if none were written:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/tmp/core.%P\n   ```\n   Then reproduce the crash. The core file lands at the path you set.\n\n3. **Analyze with `lldb`**:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /tmp/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n   Use `bt` for a backtrace, `frame variable` to inspect locals.\n\n4. **If SIP blocks core dumps**, boot into Recovery Mode and run `csrutil disable` (re-enable after debugging).\n\nThe Apple `.ips` crash reports are often sufficient — they include the faulting thread's stack trace, register state, and loaded images.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"de3c5a57-c51f-4e60-85cc-a25593c762bc","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about recovering crash dumps on macOS for NativeAOT apps when `createdump` isn't available. This seems like a general knowledge question about .NET NativeAOT debugging on macOS. Let me answer from my knowledge rather than searching the codebase, since this is a general technical question.\n\nOn macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes and `createdump` is not available (which is common since NativeAOT doesn't ship with createdump), you can rely on macOS's built-in crash reporting infrastructure.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":416},"id":"407a73fa-88fe-4d15-9a34-5009be14535c","timestamp":"2026-04-05T01:02:07.248Z","parentId":"5da2979e-2a2c-4f29-aba7-018a40540231"}
